SIMPLE: thrave
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thrave
<hw>Thrave</hw> <pr>(thr⟦amac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧rave</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧reve</ets>, Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧refi</ets>; akin to Dan. <ets>trave</ets>; cf. Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧r⟦imac⟧fa</ets> to grasp.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Twenty-four (in some places, twelve) sheaves of wheat; a shock, or
stook.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The number of two dozen; also, an indefinite number;
a bunch; a company; a throng.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The worst of a
<xex>thrave</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Landsdowne
MS.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He sends forth <qex>thraves</qex> of ballads to the sale.</q>
<rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thraw</ent>⟦br⟧
